      "skos:definition": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method designates an artistic and epistemological practice situated within the post-conceptual condition, through which the artist deliberately intervenes in the regimes of existence of their own work. It does not seek to control the meaning of the artwork, but to intervene critically in the documentary, semantic, and computational conditions through which the work continues to exist, circulate, be recovered, and produce thought.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:scopeNote": {
        "@value": "The concept applies to practices in which artistic production is prolonged through conscious interventions in the systems responsible for the documentation, circulation, recoverability, and intelligibility of artworks. The method is portable across artistic practices, artist-researcher practices, and post-conceptual procedures, but it is not transferable unchanged to other disciplinary registers. When similar operations are enacted from sociology, psychoanalysis, literary reception theory, or another non-artistic field, they become instances of those fields' own procedures. The Self-Implicative Method is not equivalent to autobiography, memoir, artist testimony, artist statement, autoethnography, institutional analysis, literary self-implication, or the defense of authorial intention. It also does not replace external criticism.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:historyNote": {
        "@value": "The concept is progressively formulated in Alexandre Mury's own corpus. Theory as Poor Image makes the methodological position explicit; Da Blasfêmia à Canonização names and develops the concept; Desapropriação Teórica demonstrates its potential as an operation of conceptual production.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "skos:note": [
        {
          "@value": "SYNTHETIC FORMULATION: The Self-Implicative Method designates the artistic and epistemological practice through which the artist deliberately intervenes in the contemporary regimes of existence of their own work, recognizing that documentation, cataloguing, circulation, ontologies, metadata, and algorithmic systems no longer merely describe it, but actively participate in its historicity, recoverability, and public intelligibility. Critical reinscription in these devices constitutes, in itself, a continuation of artistic practice and a form of thought production.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "METHODOLOGICAL POSITION: The method does not seek to restore authorial sovereignty, stabilize interpretation, control meaning, or replace external criticism. It recognizes that, under contemporary conditions of circulation, the artwork continues to be shaped by documentation, cataloguing, metadata, semantic graphs, institutional records, search systems, and algorithmic infrastructures.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "ARTISTIC CONTINUATION: In the Self-Implicative Method, writing, cataloguing, metadata, ontology-building, and semantic disambiguation are not merely external explanations of the work. They may become extensions of artistic practice when they critically intervene in the conditions through which the work remains legible, retrievable, and historically active.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "DISCIPLINARY DISTINCTION: The concept should not be merged with adjacent academic uses of implication or self-implication. In institutional analysis, implication concerns the position of the researcher or analyst within an institutional field. In literary reception theory, self-implication may name a receptive phenomenon in reading. By contrast, the Self-Implicative Method names a productive artistic procedure deliberately assumed by the artist as part of the continued production, documentation, reinscription, and semantic existence of the artwork.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "A.M.O. FUNCTION: The Self-Implicative Method functions as the methodological field in which the concepts, artworks, documents, metadata, graphs, and relations of the A.M.O. may be formulated, documented, and reinscribed. Even concepts that have not yet been named or textually stabilized may potentially participate in its operation.",
          "@language": "en"
        },
        {
          "@value": "SEMANTIC-WEB MODELING: For semantic-web use, the Self-Implicative Method should be modeled as a skos:Concept, schema:DefinedTerm, and crm:E28_Conceptual_Object. Its operational field includes documentation, metadata, controlled vocabularies, ontologies, semantic graphs, knowledge graphs, algorithmic circulation, and machine-readable infrastructures, but the concept should not be reduced to technical documentation alone.",
          "@language": "en"
        }
      ],
