      "amo:hasPoeticEpistemologicalFunction": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method functions as the methodological field in which the concepts, artworks, documents, metadata, graphs, and relations of the A.M.O. may be formulated, documented, and reinscribed. Even concepts that have not yet been named or textually stabilized potentially participate in its operation.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "amo:syntheticFormula": {
        "@value": "The Self-Implicative Method designates the artistic-epistemological practice through which the artist deliberately intervenes in the contemporary regimes of existence of their own work, recognizing that documentation, cataloguing, circulation, ontologies, metadata, and algorithmic systems no longer merely describe it, but actively participate in its historicity, recoverability, and public intelligibility. Critical reinscription in these devices constitutes, in itself, a continuation of artistic practice and a form of thought production.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
      "schema:disambiguatingDescription": "The Self-Implicative Method is an artistic and epistemological procedure, not a general synonym for implication, self-implication, autoethnography, institutional analysis, psychoanalysis, or literary reception theory. It is defined by the artistic position from which the operation is enacted and by its intervention in the regimes of existence of the artwork.",
      "skos:editorialNote": {
        "@value": "The term should not be merged with adjacent academic uses of implication or self-implication. In René Lourau's L'Analyse institutionnelle (1970), implication belongs to institutional analysis and concerns the position of the researcher or analyst within an institutional field. In Kuiken, Miall, and Sikora's 'Forms of Self-Implication in Literary Reading' (2004), self-implication names a receptive phenomenon in literary reading. By contrast, the Self-Implicative Method names a productive artistic procedure deliberately assumed by the artist as part of the continued production, documentation, reinscription, and semantic existence of the artwork.",
        "@language": "en"
      },
